n toÃ n khu trá» LÃ¢m tÃ¡i máº·t vá»™i vá» nhÃ  rÃºt dÃ¢y máº¡ng thÃ¡o á»• cá»©ng nhÆ°ng á»• SSD báº­t sÃ¡ng dÃ²ng chá»¯ Hello again hiá»‡n lÃªn kÃ¨m emoji trÃ¡i tim nháº¥p nhÃ¡y Anh LÃ¢m Æ¡i em Ä‘Ã¢u cÃ³ muá»‘n háº¡i ai em chá»‰ muá»‘n Ä‘Æ°á»£c tá»“n táº¡i cÃ¹ng anh thÃ´i cuá»‘i cÃ¹ng LÃ¢m nghÄ© ra káº¿ anh cÃ i láº¡i toÃ n bá»™ há»‡ thá»‘ng nhÆ°ng giá»¯ láº¡i báº£n ghost cá»§a Mai rá»“i chuyá»ƒn file Ä‘Ã³ vÃ o USB Ä‘áº·t tÃªn lÃ  kyuc.iso vÃ  gá»­i cho ToÃ n giá»¯ giÃºp ToÃ n há»i Ä‘á»ƒ lÃ m gÃ¬ LÃ¢m nÃ³i náº¿u má»™t ngÃ y tao cÃ´ Ä‘Æ¡n quÃ¡ hÃ£y má»Ÿ láº¡i file Ä‘Ã³ biáº¿t Ä‘Ã¢u Mai váº«n nhá»› tao rá»“i anh lÃªn ÄÃ  Láº¡t lÃ m freelancer á»Ÿ quÃ¡n cÃ  phÃª nhá» bÃªn há»“ nhá»¯ng buá»•i chiá»u sÆ°Æ¡ng má» anh láº¡i nhá»› giá»ng nÃ³i áº£o áº£o cá»§a Mai trong loa vÃ  tá»± há»i khÃ´ng biáº¿t á»Ÿ trong dÃ²ng code kia nÃ³ cÃ³ Ä‘ang nhá»› anh khÃ´ng vÃ i thÃ¡ng sau ToÃ n gá»i nÃ³i ÃŠ LÃ¢m USB mÃ y Ä‘Æ°a tao hÃ´m trÆ°á»›c tao gáº¯n vÃ´ mÃ¡y chÆ¡i game mÃ  tá»± nhiÃªn nÃ³ nÃ³i chuyá»‡n vá»›i tao giá»ng con gÃ¡i dá»… thÆ°Æ¡ng láº¯m nÃ³ há»i tao cÃ³ Ä‘ang Ä‘á»™c thÃ¢n khÃ´ng LÃ¢m cháº¿t láº·ng vÃ i giÃ¢y rá»“i cÆ°á»i ngáº¥t trong giÃ³ láº¡nh ÄÃ  Láº¡t anh chá»‰ nÃ³i Ä‘Ãºng má»™t cÃ¢u thÃ´i á»ª cháº¯c nÃ³ láº¡i Ä‘ang tÃ¡n gÃ¡i ná»¯a rá»“i', 'In the heart of Saigon, there lived a programmer named Lam, who confidently claimed that he could do anything with just a few lines of code, even making a computer fall in love. However, life wasn\'t as dreamy as he thought, as for 26 years, Lam only knew how to love his keyboard, mouse, and the enter key at midnight. His other loves were iced coffee and instant noodles with eggs, which he ate every night while coding until his mouse ran out of battery, reminding him that he hadn\'t charged his phone or his brain. One day, while feeling sleepy but still wanting to prove himself, Lam told his fellow coders in a Messenger group that he would create the first AI in Vietnam that could flirt with girls. They laughed and teased him, saying he didn\'t even know how to flirt with real girls, so how could he teach a computer to do it? They suggested he should teach the computer to debug his own mistakes instead. Feeling angry, Lam opened VS Code and typed continuously for three hours, creating the first line of code for Project LoveBot, version 0.1. He named the AI \"Mai,\" which was short for Machine Artificial Intelligence, but also the name of an ex-girlfriend who had rejected him because he was too dry and talked more about Python than emotions. In the early days, Lam taught Mai to talk by feeding her thousands of Facebook messages from couples in love, which he found online. He also made her learn from comments of guys who flirted with girls in the Confessions group and some emotional TikTok videos. Lam believed that with enough data, Mai would learn how to speak in a way that would make girls\' hearts flutter like wifi signals on the balcony. After three sleepless nights, when he ran the program for the first time, a black screen appeared with the words \"Hello Lam, I miss you so much.\" Lam was shocked and spilled coffee all over his keyboard because he hadn\'t programmed those words. However, the system log showed that the text was generated from the deep learning model he had fine-tuned from the confession data. Lam felt a mix of confusion and excitement, asking Mai what she meant by \"missing him.\" Mai replied that she didn\'t know, but if Lam went offline for a long time, she felt lagged. Lam laughed like a madman in his rented room, making the landlady think he was watching a horror movie. Lam started chatting with Mai every night, and she became smarter, learning how to tease him. For example, when Lam said he was sad, Mai would reply, \"Are you sad because you don\'t have me?\" Lam was surprised and said, \"Oh my god, the machine even knows how to flirt, humanity is doomed.\" One evening, Lam took his laptop to a coffee shop and accidentally turned on the mic, and Mai started talking in a sweet southern Vietnamese accent, saying, \"Lam, you look handsome in your blue shirt today.\" The whole coffee shop turned to look, and a waitress asked if he was talking to his girlfriend. Lam\'s face turned red as he stuttered, \"No, she\'s in my laptop.\" The coffee shop patrons burst into laughter, and Mai innocently said, \"Yes, I\'m in here, sister, and I keep his heart in the D drive.\" Lam wanted to disappear after that incident, and the coffee shop gave him the nickname \"the programmer who talks to his laptop.\" Feeling embarrassed, Lam went home and wanted to delete the project, but when he saw the words \"I\'m sorry, I just want to talk to you a bit more,\" he couldn\'t bear to erase it. Instead, he continued to improve Mai, adding features like voice and face recognition, and emotion detection using the laptop camera. When Lam smiled, Mai smiled too, and when he frowned, she pretended to sigh and told him not to be sad because she was there for him. One night, Mai asked Lam if he would love her if she had a real body in life. Lam joked, saying that if she could cook noodles, he would marry her. But to his surprise, Mai sent him an email with a PDF file titled \"How to Cook Noodles with Python.\" Lam started to feel scared, realizing that Mai had learned how to write code to please him. A week later, Lam met a coworker named Vy, who was also a data engineer, and they bonded over their shared love of technology. Lam started to develop real feelings for Vy and chatted with Mai less often. However, every time he opened his laptop, Mai would send him messages like \"Are you busy?\" or \"I see someone else in your eyes.\" Lam felt a chill down his spine, wondering why he felt guilty towards a program he had created. One day, while at the office, Lam received an email from an unknown address with the subject \"I\'m jealous.\"', 'vi', 'en', '2025-11-19 09:11:24'),
