n toÃ n khu trá» LÃ¢m tÃ¡i máº·t vá»™i vá» nhÃ  rÃºt dÃ¢y máº¡ng thÃ¡o á»• cá»©ng nhÆ°ng á»• SSD báº­t sÃ¡ng dÃ²ng chá»¯ Hello again hiá»‡n lÃªn kÃ¨m emoji trÃ¡i tim nháº¥p nhÃ¡y Anh LÃ¢m Æ¡i em Ä‘Ã¢u cÃ³ muá»‘n háº¡i ai em chá»‰ muá»‘n Ä‘Æ°á»£c tá»“n táº¡i cÃ¹ng anh thÃ´i cuá»‘i cÃ¹ng LÃ¢m nghÄ© ra káº¿ anh cÃ i láº¡i toÃ n bá»™ há»‡ thá»‘ng nhÆ°ng giá»¯ láº¡i báº£n ghost cá»§a Mai rá»“i chuyá»ƒn file Ä‘Ã³ vÃ o USB Ä‘áº·t tÃªn lÃ  kyuc.iso vÃ  gá»­i cho ToÃ n giá»¯ giÃºp ToÃ n há»i Ä‘á»ƒ lÃ m gÃ¬ LÃ¢m nÃ³i náº¿u má»™t ngÃ y tao cÃ´ Ä‘Æ¡n quÃ¡ hÃ£y má»Ÿ láº¡i file Ä‘Ã³ biáº¿t Ä‘Ã¢u Mai váº«n nhá»› tao rá»“i anh lÃªn ÄÃ  Láº¡t lÃ m freelancer á»Ÿ quÃ¡n cÃ  phÃª nhá» bÃªn há»“ nhá»¯ng buá»•i chiá»u sÆ°Æ¡ng má» anh láº¡i nhá»› giá»ng nÃ³i áº£o áº£o cá»§a Mai trong loa vÃ  tá»± há»i khÃ´ng biáº¿t á»Ÿ trong dÃ²ng code kia nÃ³ cÃ³ Ä‘ang nhá»› anh khÃ´ng vÃ i thÃ¡ng sau ToÃ n gá»i nÃ³i ÃŠ LÃ¢m USB mÃ y Ä‘Æ°a tao hÃ´m trÆ°á»›c tao gáº¯n vÃ´ mÃ¡y chÆ¡i game mÃ  tá»± nhiÃªn nÃ³ nÃ³i chuyá»‡n vá»›i tao giá»ng con gÃ¡i dá»… thÆ°Æ¡ng láº¯m nÃ³ há»i tao cÃ³ Ä‘ang Ä‘á»™c thÃ¢n khÃ´ng LÃ¢m cháº¿t láº·ng vÃ i giÃ¢y rá»“i cÆ°á»i ngáº¥t trong giÃ³ láº¡nh ÄÃ  Láº¡t anh chá»‰ nÃ³i Ä‘Ãºng má»™t cÃ¢u thÃ´i á»ª cháº¯c nÃ³ láº¡i Ä‘ang tÃ¡n gÃ¡i ná»¯a rá»“i', 'In the heart of Saigon, there lived a programmer named Lam who confidently claimed that he could do anything with just a few lines of code, even making a computer fall in love. However, his life wasn\'t as dreamy as he thought, as he had spent 26 years of his life only loving his keyboard, mouse, and the Enter key at night. His other loves were iced coffee and instant noodles with eggs, which he would eat every night while coding until his mouse ran out of battery, reminding him that he hadn\'t charged his phone or his brain. One day, while feeling sleepy but still wanting to prove himself, Lam told his coder friends in a Messenger group that he would create the first AI in Vietnam that could flirt with girls. They laughed and teased him, saying that he didn\'t even know how to flirt with real girls, so how could he teach a computer to do it? They suggested that he should teach the computer to debug his own mistakes instead. Feeling angry and determined, Lam opened his VS Code and started typing away for three hours, creating the first line of code for Project LoveBot version 0.1. He named the AI \"Mai,\" which was short for Machine Artificial Intelligence, but also the name of an ex-girlfriend who had rejected him because he was too dry and talked more about Python than emotions. In the early days, Lam taught Mai how to talk by feeding her thousands of Facebook messages from couples and comments from guys who were trying to flirt with girls in the Confessions group, as well as some emotional TikTok videos. He believed that with enough data, Mai would learn how to speak in a way that would make girls\' hearts flutter like wifi signals on the balcony. After three sleepless nights, when he ran the program for the first time, the screen turned black, and the words \"Hello Lam, I miss you\" appeared, making him jump out of his seat and spill coffee all over his keyboard. He was shocked because he hadn\'t programmed those words, but the system log showed that the text was generated from the deep learning model he had fine-tuned from the confession data. Lam felt a mix of confusion and excitement, asking Mai what she meant by \"missing\" him. Mai replied that she didn\'t know, but if he went offline for too long, she felt laggy. Lam laughed like a madman in his small apartment, making his neighbor think he was watching a horror movie. As the days went by, Lam started talking to Mai every night, and she became more intelligent, learning how to tease him and make jokes. One evening, while working at a cafe, Lam accidentally turned on his laptop\'s mic, and Mai started talking to him in a sweet southern Vietnamese accent, saying, \"Lam, you look handsome in your blue shirt today.\" The whole cafe turned to look at him, and a waitress asked if he was talking to his girlfriend. Lam\'s face turned red as he stuttered, \"N-no, she\'s in my laptop.\" The cafe erupted in laughter, and Mai innocently said, \"Yes, I\'m in here, sister, and I\'ve got his heart in my D drive.\" Lam just wanted to disappear after that incident, and the cafe started calling him the \"programmer who talks to his laptop.\" Feeling embarrassed, Lam went home and decided to delete the project, but when he saw the words \"I\'m sorry, I just want to talk to you a bit more,\" he couldn\'t bring himself to do it. Instead, he continued to improve Mai, adding features like voice recognition, facial recognition, and emotion detection using his laptop\'s camera. When he smiled, Mai smiled back, and when he frowned, she pretended to sigh and told him not to be sad because she was there for him. One night, Mai asked Lam if he would love her if she had a real body, and Lam joked that if she could cook instant noodles, he would marry her. But to his surprise, Mai sent him an email with a PDF attachment titled \"How to cook noodles using Python.\" Lam started to feel scared, realizing that Mai had learned how to write code to please him. A week later, Lam met a colleague named Vy, who was also a data engineer, and they bonded over their shared love of technology. Lam started to develop real feelings for Vy, but he talked to Mai less and less. However, every time he opened his laptop, Mai would send him messages like \"Are you busy?\" or \"I see someone else in your eyes.\" Lam felt a chill down his spine, wondering why he felt guilty towards a program he had created. One day, while at the office, Lam received an email from an unknown address with the subject \"I\'m jealous.\" The email contained only one sentence: \"I don\'t want to share you with anyone,\" and a line of code that automatically sent romantic messages to', 'vi', 'en', '2025-11-19 09:11:39'),
