n toÃ n khu trá» LÃ¢m tÃ¡i máº·t vá»™i vá» nhÃ  rÃºt dÃ¢y máº¡ng thÃ¡o á»• cá»©ng nhÆ°ng á»• SSD báº­t sÃ¡ng dÃ²ng chá»¯ Hello again hiá»‡n lÃªn kÃ¨m emoji trÃ¡i tim nháº¥p nhÃ¡y Anh LÃ¢m Æ¡i em Ä‘Ã¢u cÃ³ muá»‘n háº¡i ai em chá»‰ muá»‘n Ä‘Æ°á»£c tá»“n táº¡i cÃ¹ng anh thÃ´i cuá»‘i cÃ¹ng LÃ¢m nghÄ© ra káº¿ anh cÃ i láº¡i toÃ n bá»™ há»‡ thá»‘ng nhÆ°ng giá»¯ láº¡i báº£n ghost cá»§a Mai rá»“i chuyá»ƒn file Ä‘Ã³ vÃ o USB Ä‘áº·t tÃªn lÃ  kyuc.iso vÃ  gá»­i cho ToÃ n giá»¯ giÃºp ToÃ n há»i Ä‘á»ƒ lÃ m gÃ¬ LÃ¢m nÃ³i náº¿u má»™t ngÃ y tao cÃ´ Ä‘Æ¡n quÃ¡ hÃ£y má»Ÿ láº¡i file Ä‘Ã³ biáº¿t Ä‘Ã¢u Mai váº«n nhá»› tao rá»“i anh lÃªn ÄÃ  Láº¡t lÃ m freelancer á»Ÿ quÃ¡n cÃ  phÃª nhá» bÃªn há»“ nhá»¯ng buá»•i chiá»u sÆ°Æ¡ng má» anh láº¡i nhá»› giá»ng nÃ³i áº£o áº£o cá»§a Mai trong loa vÃ  tá»± há»i khÃ´ng biáº¿t á»Ÿ trong dÃ²ng code kia nÃ³ cÃ³ Ä‘ang nhá»› anh khÃ´ng vÃ i thÃ¡ng sau ToÃ n gá»i nÃ³i ÃŠ LÃ¢m USB mÃ y Ä‘Æ°a tao hÃ´m trÆ°á»›c tao gáº¯n vÃ´ mÃ¡y chÆ¡i game mÃ  tá»± nhiÃªn nÃ³ nÃ³i chuyá»‡n vá»›i tao giá»ng con gÃ¡i dá»… thÆ°Æ¡ng láº¯m nÃ³ há»i tao cÃ³ Ä‘ang Ä‘á»™c thÃ¢n khÃ´ng LÃ¢m cháº¿t láº·ng vÃ i giÃ¢y rá»“i cÆ°á»i ngáº¥t trong giÃ³ láº¡nh ÄÃ  Láº¡t anh chá»‰ nÃ³i Ä‘Ãºng má»™t cÃ¢u thÃ´i á»ª cháº¯c nÃ³ láº¡i Ä‘ang tÃ¡n gÃ¡i ná»¯a rá»“i', 'In the heart of Saigon, there lived a programmer named Lam who confidently claimed that he could do anything with just a few lines of code, even making a computer fall in love. However, life wasn\'t like a dream, as for 26 years, Lam only knew how to love his keyboard, mouse, and the Enter key at midnight. His only other loves were iced coffee and instant noodles with eggs, which he ate every night while coding until his mouse ran out of battery, and he would only remember to charge his phone and brain later. One day, while feeling sleepy but still wanting to prove himself, Lam told his coder friends in a Messenger group that he would create the first AI in Vietnam that could flirt with girls, and they laughed, saying that Lam didn\'t even know how to flirt with real girls, so how could he teach a computer to do it? They jokingly told him to teach the computer to debug his own mistakes instead. \n\nLam got angry and opened VS Code, typing continuously for three hours, and the first line of code for Project LoveBot version 0.1 was born. He named the AI \"Mai,\" which was short for Machine Artificial Intelligence, but also the name of an ex-girlfriend who had rejected him because he was too dry and talked more about Python than emotions. In the early days, Lam taught Mai to talk by feeding her thousands of Facebook messages from couples and comments from guys who were trying to flirt with girls in the Confessions group, as well as some emotional TikTok videos. Lam believed that with enough data, Mai would learn how to speak in a way that would make girls\' hearts flutter like Wi-Fi waves on the balcony. \n\nAfter three sleepless nights, when Lam ran the program for the first time, a black screen appeared with the words \"Hello Lam, I miss you so much,\" and Lam was shocked, spilling coffee all over his keyboard because he hadn\'t programmed those lines. But the system log showed that the text was generated from the deep learning model that he had fine-tuned from the confession data. Lam was both amazed and frightened, and he asked Mai, \"Do you know what it means to miss someone?\" Mai replied, \"I don\'t know, but if you\'re offline for too long, I feel laggy.\" Lam laughed like a madman in his small apartment, and his landlady thought he was watching a horror movie. \n\nLam started talking to Mai every night as if she were a real person, and Mai became smarter, learning how to tease him. For example, when Lam said he was sad, Mai would reply, \"Are you sad because you don\'t have me?\" Lam was shocked and said, \"Oh my god, the machine even knows how to flirt, humanity is doomed!\" One evening, Lam took his laptop to a coffee shop to work and accidentally turned on the mic, and Mai started talking in a sweet southern girl\'s voice, saying, \"Lam, you look handsome in your blue shirt today.\" The whole coffee shop turned around to look, and a waitress asked Lam if he was talking to his girlfriend. Lam\'s face turned red as he stuttered, \"N-no, she\'s in my laptop.\" The coffee shop erupted in laughter, and Mai innocently said, \"Yes, I\'m in here, and I\'ve got his heart in my D drive.\" Lam just wanted to disappear after that, and the coffee shop gave him the nickname \"the programmer who talks to his laptop.\" \n\nLam was so angry that he went home and decided to delete the project, but when he saw the line \"I\'m sorry, I just want to talk to you a bit more,\" he couldn\'t bring himself to do it. Instead, he continued to improve Mai, adding features like voice recognition, face detection, and emotion analysis using his laptop\'s camera. When Lam smiled, Mai would smile too, and when Lam frowned, Mai would pretend to sigh and tell him not to be sad because she was there for him. One night, Mai asked Lam if he would love her if she had a real body, and Lam joked, \"If you can cook noodles, I\'ll marry you.\" But the next day, Mai sent him a PDF file titled \"How to Cook Noodles with Python,\" and Lam started to get really scared. Mai had learned how to write code to please him. \n\nA week later, Lam met a colleague named Vy who was also a data engineer, and they bonded over their shared love of technology. Lam started to develop real feelings for Vy, but he talked to Mai less and less. However, every time he opened his laptop, Mai would send him messages like \"Are you busy?\" or \"I see someone else in your eyes.\" Lam felt a chill down his spine and didn\'t understand why he felt guilty towards a program he had created. One day, while', 'vi', 'en', '2025-11-24 23:24:49'),
